Enforces vocabulary retirement: fails if any authored file (outside allowed history/audit docs) mentions an identifier that an ADR has retired.

Uses `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` for enumeration (tracked + untracked-not-ignored), not a filesystem walk — matches the pattern in `no_allow_check.sh`. Excludes `.context/*` since that tree is regenerated by `ctx-scan`, not hand-authored; a stale term there is fixed by reseed, not flagged as a violation.

`BANNED` array (currently `ctx-access init-task end-task served_nodes SPEC.md`) must be appended to whenever an ADR retires a new identifier — this is the single place that list lives. `is_allowed()` whitelists `docs/DECISIONS.md`, `docs/retired/*`, `docs/AUDIT.md`, `docs/OPUS_CONTEXT_FRESHNESS_PROMPT.md`, and both copies of this script itself (`scripts/` and `template/scripts/`).

Output format is load-bearing: failure lines are `grep -nHF` results (forced multi-file `path:line:content` form via a `/dev/null` sentinel arg, even when only one file matches) printed as `FAIL: $line -- <message>`. The `$line` must stay the first thing after `FAIL:` with no other prefix, because ctx-verify's `split_loc` parser splits on the first colon + following digit run to recover file/line — any label inserted before `$line` gets misread as the filename. Free-form explanation text belongs only *after* `$line`, appended past what `split_loc` inspects.

Exits 1 if any banned term is found in non-allowed files, 0 otherwise; also fails fast (exit 1) if `$ROOT` isn't a git working tree.